0}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:1129"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "M2 receptor", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9871301651000977, "span": {"begin": 667, "end": 678}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:1128"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "muscarinic receptors", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9927133917808533, "span": {"begin": 748, "end": 768}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:1129"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "M2 receptor", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9699352979660034, "span": {"begin": 800, "end": 811}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:10663"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "G-protein-coupled receptor", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9840471148490906, "span": {"begin": 829, "end": 855}}, {"id": ["mesh:D011188"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "potassium", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9992290735244751, "span": {"begin": 867, "end": 876}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "heart smooth muscle cell", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.7618831396102905, "span": {"begin": 925, "end": 949}}, {"id": ["mim:115000", "mesh:D001145"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "arrhythmia", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9999696016311646, "span": {"begin": 981, "end": 991}}, {"id": ["mesh:D001919"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "bradycardia", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9999803900718689, "span": {"begin": 1018, "end": 1029}}], "text": "In the context of cholinergic toxicity induced by AChE inhibition, increased cholinergic signaling leads to impaired cardiovascular function because acetylcholine is an important signalling molecule in the heart. The vagus nerve and cardiomyocytes produce neuronal and non-neuronal acetylcholine, respectively (Saw, 2018, Beckmann, 2013). Cardiac function is controlled by the sympathetic and parasympathetic nervous systems.The heart is innervated by the vagus nerve, a cholinergic nerve that activates muscarinic acetylcholine receptors (M-ChR) on heart smooth muscle tissue.      While five different muscarinic receptors classes have been identified (M1-M5), the M2 receptor is most abundant in the heart and it is the most well-studied of the muscarinic receptors (Dhein, 2001, Zang, 2005). The M2 receptor is an inhibitory G-protein-coupled receptor that opens potassium channels in the cell membrane, which alters the heart smooth muscle cell electrophysiology and leads to arrhythmia and decreased heart rate (bradycardia) (Lodish, Zang, 2005).&nbsp;", "timestamp": "Mon Jun 08 14:29:38 +0000 2026"}